  2017,"10",/general-conference/2017/10/the-priesthood-and-the-saviors-atoning-power,Elder Dale G. Renlund,48,"SeeThe Teachings of Ezra Taft Benson(1988), 223; Joseph Fielding Smith, in Conference Report, Apr. 1970, 59;Teachings of the Prophet Joseph Smith,sel. Joseph Fielding Smith (1976), 323."
  2017,"10",/general-conference/2017/10/the-priesthood-and-the-saviors-atoning-power,Elder Dale G. Renlund,49,"There is no scriptural reference or account of the recipient swearing an oath as he makes the Melchizedek Priesthood covenant. Instead, in Joseph Smith Translation, Genesis 14:27–31 (in the Bible appendix);Psalm 110:1, 4;Hebrews 7:21; andDoctrine and Covenants 84:40, it is God who swears an oath as He makes the covenant with the recipient. Elder Bruce R. McConkie said: “The Lord swears with an oath in his own name … that everyone who keeps the covenant made in connection with the Melchizedek Priesthood shall inherit, receive, and possess all things in his everlasting kingdom. … God swore with an oath that Christ would be exalted, and he swears anew, at the time each of us receives the Melchizedek Priesthood, that we will have a like exaltation if we are true and faithful in all things” (“The Doctrine of the Priesthood,” 33)."
  2017,"10",/general-conference/2017/10/the-priesthood-and-the-saviors-atoning-power,Elder Dale G. Renlund,50,"SeeDoctrine and Covenants 84:41–42. Repentance is always possible for those willing to change. See, for instance, Dale G. Renlund, “Repentance: A Joyful Choice,”EnsignorLiahona,Nov. 2016, 121–24."
